Configuration files (.tlc)
----------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------

Incompressible
----------------------------------------------------------------
- <<couette.tcl>>

- <<poiseuille.tcl>>

Note: the initial particle distribution for incompressible simulations is
created within the program. Therefore there is no need to pass a second argument
to the main function specifying an external file for initial conditons (.ivs)
(ivs=Initial Values Shocktube, <<ics>> (<<c>> for condition) does already
exist as standard file ending)


Compressible
----------------------------------------------------------------
- <<1Dshock.tcl>>
  for a 1 D shock tube calculation with a purely 1D particle distribution. The
  initial condition files which can be passed to the main function in this
  case are
  *  <<1DshockMConst.ivs>>
  *  <<1DshockSpaceConst.ivs>>

- <<q1Dshock.tcl>>
  for a 1D shock tube calculation with a 2D particle distribution and
  periodical boundary condition in the second direction. In this
  case the possible initial condition files are:
  *  <<q1DshockSpaceConst.ivs>>
  *  <<q1DshockMConst.ivs>>
  
#################################################################  


Initial condition files (.ivs)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Incompressible
-----------------------------------------------------------------

No external initial condition file (.ivs)


Compressible
-----------------------------------------------------------------

For the compressible shock tube case there are different possibilities
to initilaize the particle field. Therefore initial conditions are created by
the user prior to the actual simulation and are then passed to the main
function. The following initial particle distributions are available

Purely 1D distribution:
-----------------------
- constant particle mass, different left hand side and right hand side
  spacing. The file is called <<1DshockMConst.ivs>> and is created by
   <<createIC1D_mConst.cpp>>

  for the corresponding perturbation study (perturbation on particle position)
  use 
  <<createIC1D_mConstRAND.cpp>>

- constant particle spacing, different left hand side and right hand side
  particle masses. The file is called <<1DshockSpaceConst.ivs>> and is created by
  <<createIC1D_SpaceConst.cpp>>

  for the corresponding perturbation study (perturbation on particle position)
  use 
  <<createIC1D_SpaceConstRAND.cpp>>


2D distribution:
----------------
- constant particle mass for all the domain, different left hand side and 
  right hand side spacing. The file is called <<q1DshockMConst.ivs>> and created by
  <<createICq1D_mConst.cpp>>

- constant particle spacing for all the domain, different left hand side and 
  right hand side particle mass. The file is called <<q1DshockSpaceConst.ivs>> and
  created by <<createICq1D_SpaceConst.cpp>>


Porcedure to follow for a simulation with .ivs files
-----------------------------------------------------------------
1. Creating the initial condition file (.ivs)
   To create the desired initial condition file, one has to go into the
   <<sph-blitz/scripts>> folder, compile (<<make>>) and run the corresponding
   <<createICxxxx.cpp>> program.
   The .ivs file is then created in the <<sph-blitz/cases>> folder

2. Handing the .ivs fail over to the main function
   This is done by adding the .ivs file name as the second argument during the
   main function call
   for example:
    ./sph <<project_name>> << xxxxx.ivs>>
    ./sph ../cases/q1Dshock ../cases q1DshockSpaceConst.ivs

	
